%I A397208 #9 Jun 28 2026 19:39:18
%S A397208 0,0,1,1,0,1,2,0,1,1,1,2,2,0,2,1,1,2,0,2,3,2,1,3,2,3,2,2,3,3,3,3,3,2,
%T A397208 1,3,4,1,3,1,3,4,2,4,3,3,2,4,3,5,5,6,4,3,5,5,4,4,5,5,2,2,2,4,6,4,3,4,
%U A397208 4,4,4,6,6,4,3,5,6,7,5,7,5,6,4,5,6,4,6,5
%N A397208 a(n) is the number of primes q < p = prime(n) such that (p + q)/4 is prime.
%C A397208 Equivalently, a(n) is the number of representations of p = prime(n) in the form p = 4*r - q, where q < p and q and r are primes.
%C A397208 Since r = (p + q)/4 is an integer, we need p + q == 0 (mod 4). Thus for odd p, the prime q must lie in the opposite residue class modulo 4. This condition restricts q to a single residue class modulo 4 for each p, so the values of a(n) are influenced by the distribution of primes in these classes (see A038698).
%C A397208 Conjecture: The only zeros occur for p = 2, 3, 11, 19, 43, 67. Verified numerically for n <= 10000 (p <= 104729).
%C A397208 The constant 0.39 in the asymptotic formula appears to arise from a Hardy-Littlewood type singular series reflecting local congruence restrictions on the primes q and r. This is supported by numerical data up to n = 10000, showing a close fit between empirical values and the asymptotic curve (see graph).
%C A397208 Conjecture: Every nonnegative integer occurs in this sequence.
%H A397208 Felix Huber, <a href="/A397208/b397208.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397208 Felix Huber, <a href="/A397208/a397208.pdf">Growth of a(n)</a>
%F A397208 Heuristic asymptotic: a(n) ~ 0.39*prime(n)/(log(prime(n)))^2.
%e A397208 a(7) = 2, since p = 17 and the valid primes q are 3 and 11: (17 + 3)/4 = 5 and (17 + 11)/4 = 7 are both prime.
%e A397208 a(10) = 1, since p = 29 and the only valid prime q is 23: (29 + 23)/4 = 13 is prime.
%p A397208 A397208 := proc(n)
%p A397208     local i, p;
%p A397208     p := ithprime(n);
%p A397208     add(`if`(isprime(p - 2 - 4*i) and isprime((p + (p - 2 - 4*i))/4), 1, 0), i = 0 .. floor((p - 3)/4));
%p A397208 end proc:
%p A397208 seq(A397208(n), n = 1 .. 88);
%Y A397208 Cf. A000040, A000720, A002144, A002145, A038698, A045917, A098428, A191473, A339414, A397209.
%K A397208 nonn,easy
%O A397208 1,7
%A A397208 _Felix Huber_, Jun 23 2026
